      textEn: [
        "Outside the window stood towering willows. The courtyard sat in a mountain gully, and the hillsides were covered with trees. Sitting cross-legged on the kang, we felt like we were on a boat, surrounded by waves of green. When the wind blew, the treetops rustled like ocean surf, and light shimmered through the leaves.",
        "I knew the larger environment of this gully. This was northwestern Shanxi, a place frequently ravaged by Siberian winds, where drought, frost, and sandstorms—monsters hostile to life—held dominion. In the past, windblown sand could bury a town up to its walls. The local county records state: 'When great winds blow, they can push cattle and horses backward, or lift them two or three zhang before dropping them.' Yet in this perilous place, the thin old man sitting across from me, cradling a long-stemmed pipe, had created this green oasis.",
        "I also knew the small world of this courtyard. Of the row of three rooms, only the old man remained. Every morning he would grab a handful of firewood to cook, then carry his rations and shoulder his shovel to head up the gully. In the evening he'd return, eat, smoke, and sleep. At sixty-five, he organized seven old men to start reclaiming this gully; five of them have since passed away. His admirable wife had weathered every storm with him; one day, when he came home from planting, he found her lying still on the kang, gone. Now eighty-one, he knew the day would come when he too could no longer rise. His only daughter had come from the city repeatedly to take him to a comfortable retirement. He refused. He felt that planting trees was his destiny, and the green mountains behind the house were his final resting place.",
        "He tapped his pipe unhurriedly as he spoke, while the village cadre respectfully filled in details... Fifteen years! He had greened eight gullies, planted seven windbreak belts and 3,700 mu of forest network—what an extraordinary miracle. Last winter, he used forestry income to buy a television for every household in the village. And he still had grand plans—to keep planting trees until he could no longer stand.",
        "After talking inside, the old man walked us into the gully to see the trees. Poplars and willows, thick as arms and legs, stood strong in the hollows and on the slopes. You couldn't see their roots—mud from mountain floods had buried the lower halves of the trunks, yet the trees had bravely withstood the torrent. The mountain had lost its original slope, shaped instead by layers of trees forming terraces. The old man said, 'The silt beneath these trees is two meters thick—it's all good soil!' Yes, by preserving this yellow earth, we have these green trees; with these green trees, we hold on to this land.",
        "After viewing the trees, we said goodbye at the village entrance. The old man, leaning on his cane, slowly walked into his little courtyard where green breezes rippled. My nose stung with emotion—perhaps after he went in, he would never come out again. As a simple mountain farmer, this was how he realized his worth. He had already transformed his life into something else. He truly coexisted with the mountains and shone with the sun and moon.",
        "This ordinary old man taught me: the green mountains never grow old."
      ],
