      textEn: [
        "The Horse Whip\nAncient Chinese people frequently rode horses. But riding a horse cannot be performed on stage—the stage is too small for a horse to gallop, and actors fear a real horse might lose control. Peking opera inherited and developed the expressive techniques of traditional Chinese theater, and brilliantly solved this problem with a simple riding crop. This performance method perfectly embodies Chinese aesthetics. The enormous horse is entirely omitted, yet the rider's distinctive, elegant posture is vividly displayed. This virtual whip gives actors infinite freedom in performance: it can be raised high or held low; you can ride all day and still be at your front door, or lift your hand once and have traveled a hundred miles. The whip itself possesses a decorative beauty, and different characters have each developed their own established ways of using it.",
        "The horse whip is a tangible prop, something you can feel and use. Peking opera also has virtual props that are equally tangible in their absence. In 'Picking Up the Jade Bracelet,' a girl sews a shoe sole—the sole is real, but the needle and thread are imaginary. Yet in the actor's hands, 'nothing' far surpasses 'something.'",
        "Or take the wine cups and pots at a feast. The host orders, 'Set the banquet!' and servants bring cups and pots onto the stage. Host and guests raise their cups and drink, cup after cup, yet no one ever eats any food—and still the guests are 'full.' Peking opera generally does not bring rice bowls on stage. When one is actually used, the actor must 'act intensely' with it. In 'Jin Yu Nu,' the young male actor drinks bean juice from a bowl, then licks the chopsticks. Without that 'lick,' there would be no reason to bring the bowl on stage at all.",
        "Striking a Pose\nPeking opera has another remarkable feature: Two fighters are in the thick of combat, so fierce that not even wind or rain could penetrate. The audience is on the edge of their seats, scarcely daring to breathe, eyes wide open, afraid that in the blink of an eye one will 'kill' the other. Yet strangely, just when the fight is at its fiercest, the tense, rhythmic drumbeats suddenly stop, and the actors freeze—face to face, eyes locked, weapons poised, as if some spell has immobilized them all!",
        "The question is fair, but this is precisely the brilliance of Peking opera artistry. As the saying goes, 'Stillness is better than motion,' and as an ancient poem states, 'At such a moment, silence surpasses sound.' Stillness accentuates the fighters' supreme skill and their confidence in victory.",
        "There is also the 'weapon exit,' which can be seen as a dynamic pose. During a battle, one side is defeated and runs off. But the victor does not give chase. Instead, they stay center stage and twirl their weapon—a saber or spear—in a whirlwind of motion. Is this even theater? Isn't it more like acrobatics? Exactly right! This is the acrobatic element in Peking opera, a tradition since ancient times that survives today. Its purpose is to showcase the hero's daring spirit."
      ],
